<!-- ABOUT -->
<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Lakshadweep</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">India's <em>Coral Crown</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Lakshadweep — meaning "A Hundred Thousand Islands" in Sanskrit — is India's smallest Union Territory by area and its only coral atoll system. A necklace of 36 tiny coral islands, 12 atolls, 3 reefs and 5 submerged banks scattered across 32 square kilometres of land in the vast Arabian Sea, Lakshadweep sits 200 to 440 kilometres west of the Kerala coast. Only 10 of the 36 islands are inhabited. The total population of barely 65,000 people — all Muslim, all Malayalam-speaking, all descended from ancient Keralite settlers who converted to Islam centuries ago — makes Lakshadweep the least populated Union Territory in India. What the islands lack in size they more than compensate for in natural splendour. The lagoons of Lakshadweep — enclosed saltwater bodies between the coral reef and the island — are among the clearest waters on earth, with visibility of 40-50 metres and a turquoise so vivid it appears artificial. The coral reefs here contain over 600 species of coral fish, sea turtles, dolphins, whale sharks, manta rays, reef sharks and dugongs (sea cows). The coral atoll system itself — India's only one — formed over millions of years as volcanic seamounts subsided and coral grew upward to maintain sea level, creating some of the world's most spectacular underwater landscapes. The islands are also home to the last significant population of the coconut crab in India — the world's largest land invertebrate. Lakshadweep requires an entry permit for all Indian visitors (obtained easily in advance) and a separate permit for non-Indians. Some islands are restricted entirely. The result is that these are among the least-visited and best-preserved tropical islands in Asia — the Maldives of India, but wilder, quieter and entirely authentic.</p>

  <div class="permit-note">
    <strong>⚠️ Entry Permit Required:</strong> All visitors to Lakshadweep — Indian and foreign — must obtain an Entry Permit before arrival. Indian citizens apply through the Lakshadweep Administration or authorised tour operators. Foreign nationals require additional clearances. Only certain islands are open to tourists: <strong>Agatti, Bangaram, Kadmat, Kalpeni, Kavaratti, Minicoy and Thinnakara.</strong> Islands like Andrott, Amini, Chetlat, Kiltan and Bitra are closed to tourists to protect the resident communities.
  </div>
</section>

