const placesData=[
  {emoji:"🤿",name:"Agatti & Bangaram Coral Reefs",location:"Northern Lakshadweep",desc:"India's finest scuba diving and snorkelling — the coral reefs around Agatti and Bangaram islands offer 40-50 metre visibility in peak season with coral gardens of extraordinary diversity: 600+ species of fish, sea turtles resting on the reef, white-tip reef sharks circling the drop-offs, manta rays cruising the channel, and Napoleon wrasse of enormous size. The Bangaram reef drop-off — where the coral wall plunges 40 metres into the deep blue — is one of the most dramatic dive sites in India.",fee:["Paid — dive packages","Entry Permit required"]},
  {emoji:"🏝️",name:"Bangaram Atoll — Uninhabited Paradise",location:"Bangaram Island",desc:"The most exclusive island experience in India — Bangaram is an uninhabited coral island with a single eco-resort that has operated since 1983. The island is entirely surrounded by a living coral reef with a turquoise lagoon so clear that the bottom is visible at 8 metres depth. No vehicles, no roads, no noise except the ocean. Coconut crabs (the world's largest land invertebrate) wander the beach at night. Sea turtles nest on the south beach. The only way to experience an uninhabited tropical island in India.",fee:["Resort accommodation required","Entry Permit required"]},
  {emoji:"🌊",name:"Kalpeni Lagoon — Multi-Atoll System",location:"Kalpeni Island",desc:"Kalpeni's extraordinary geography — three small islands (Kalpeni, Cheriyam and Tilakkam) sharing a single large lagoon — creates one of the most spectacular lagoon environments in Asia. The shallow lagoon between the islands is a natural snorkelling park with coral gardens, sea grass beds (feeding ground for dugongs), reef fish in extraordinary numbers and excellent visibility. The outer reef at Kalpeni receives strong currents that bring large pelagic fish including tuna, barracuda and occasional whale sharks.",fee:["Entry Permit required","Boat charges apply"]},
  {emoji:"🏗️",name:"Minicoy Lighthouse",location:"Minicoy Island",desc:"The Minicoy Lighthouse — built by the British in 1885 — is 52 metres tall and required 300 steps to climb. It stands on the southern tip of Minicoy Island and offers the most panoramic view in Lakshadweep — the entire atoll spread below, the deep blue of the Arabian Sea on one side and the turquoise lagoon on the other. Minicoy is the southernmost inhabited island of India before the Maldives, and the lighthouse guided ships through the Eight Degree Channel for over a century.",fee:["Rs.10 entry"]},
  {emoji:"🐢",name:"Sea Turtle Nesting Beaches",location:"Multiple islands",desc:"Lakshadweep is a critical nesting site for two sea turtle species — the green turtle (Chelonia mydas) and the hawksbill turtle (Eretmochelys imbricata). Both species are critically endangered and the Lakshadweep reefs support feeding populations of hundreds of individuals. Nesting occurs on several beaches, particularly at Bangaram, Thinnakara and the uninhabited islands. The Forest Department conducts nest monitoring and hatchery protection programs. Night turtle watching (with strict protocols) is one of the most extraordinary wildlife experiences available.",fee:["Free with Forest Dept. escort","Entry Permit required"]},
  {emoji:"🕌",name:"Ujra Mosque — Kavaratti",location:"Kavaratti Island",desc:"Kavaratti's Ujra Mosque is the most elaborately decorated of the 52 mosques on the capital island — built of local coral and wood with an interior of exquisite wooden carving that reflects the island's long tradition of master craftsmanship. The ceiling is carved from driftwood collected from the sea, shaped by artisans who worked without nails or metal fasteners. Lakshadweep has more mosques per square kilometre than virtually anywhere in India — the entire population is Muslim, and religious life is the heartbeat of island society.",fee:["Free — modest dress required"]},
  {emoji:"🐠",name:"Lakshadweep Marine Aquarium",location:"Kavaratti Island",desc:"The Lakshadweep Marine Aquarium in Kavaratti is one of the finest in India for displaying the extraordinary biodiversity of coral reef ecosystems — living coral displays, reef fish of every colour and size, sea anemones with clownfish, moray eels in crevices and regular displays of local marine species. It also functions as a coral propagation and reef restoration centre, where coral fragments are grown on underwater frames before transplantation to damaged reef sections. India's most important coral conservation facility.",fee:["Rs.20 Indians","Rs.100 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"⛵",name:"Traditional Thoni & Odi Boat Building",location:"Kavaratti & Agatti",desc:"Lakshadweep's traditional boat-building tradition — constructing the thoni (a large wooden sailing vessel) and odi (outrigger canoe) without nails, using only wooden pegs and coconut fibre caulking — is one of the most sophisticated traditional marine craft traditions in India. The boats are built entirely from locally available materials: coconut wood for the hull, coir (coconut fibre) for lashing and caulking, and cotton sailcloth. Kavaratti's boat yard is one of the last places in India where this tradition is actively practised.",fee:["Free to observe"]},
];

const artsData=[
  {emoji:"🥁",name:"Lava Dance (Kolkali & Parichakali)",location:"All islands",desc:"The traditional martial dance of Lakshadweep — Kolkali (performed with short sticks) and Parichakali (performed with swords and shields) are the most distinctive performing arts of the islands. Both are performed by men in traditional white dress with elaborate footwork, striking movements and rhythmic chanting. Kolkali involves 16 or more performers striking sticks in synchronised patterns as they move in a circle. The dances are performed at weddings, festivals and important celebrations — deeply rooted in the islands' Islamic cultural tradition."},
  {emoji:"🪵",name:"Coral & Wood Carving",location:"Kavaratti, Minicoy",desc:"The Lakshadweep tradition of carving from coral stone and driftwood has produced some of the most distinctive decorative art in India — mosque interiors with carved wooden ceilings and screens, coral stone pillars with geometric Islamic patterns, and wooden furniture with intricate inlay work. The use of naturally available materials — coral stone from the reef, driftwood from the ocean — and the Islamic tradition of geometric (non-figurative) art creates a distinctive aesthetic found nowhere else in India."},
  {emoji:"🧵",name:"Coir Craft — Coconut Fibre Weaving",location:"All islands",desc:"Coconut palm is the defining natural resource of Lakshadweep — and the tradition of working with coir (coconut fibre) is deeply embedded in island life. Ropes, mats, baskets, bags and traditional boat caulking are all made from coir using techniques passed down through generations. The coir rope-making of Lakshadweep — twisted by hand into ropes of extraordinary strength — is sold across India. The coconut palm also provides fronds for thatching, trunk for construction, and oil for cooking and traditional medicine."},
  {emoji:"🐚",name:"Shell Craft & Marine Jewellery",location:"Kavaratti market",desc:"The extraordinary variety of shells found in Lakshadweep's reefs — cowries, turbans, cones, olives, volutes and hundreds of other species — have historically been used for craft, currency and decoration. Today shell craft (using only shells found naturally washed up on beaches, not collected from live animals) includes jewellery, decorative items and traditional implements. The cowrie shell has particular cultural significance — historically used as currency across the Indian Ocean world, cowries from Lakshadweep were a major trade commodity for centuries."},
  {emoji:"⛵",name:"Traditional Navigation & Seamanship",location:"All islands",desc:"The islanders of Lakshadweep are among India's most accomplished traditional mariners — navigating the Arabian Sea using stars, ocean swells, bird behaviour and traditional knowledge accumulated over centuries. The outrigger canoe (odi) and the large sailing vessel (thoni) were the primary means of inter-island travel for centuries, requiring intimate knowledge of winds, currents and reef navigation. This maritime knowledge is gradually being documented by researchers as motor vessels replace traditional sailing craft."},
  {emoji:"🎵",name:"Oppana — Islamic Wedding Music",location:"All islands",desc:"Oppana is the traditional music and dance of Lakshadweep's Muslim community — performed at weddings by women in a circle around the bride, clapping hands in rhythmic patterns and singing songs of praise and celebration in Malayalam. The form is also found in coastal Kerala's Muslim communities but has a distinctively island character in Lakshadweep. The songs celebrate the bride's beauty, invoke divine blessings and narrate the history of the community. Oppana is performed only at weddings — it is not a public entertainment but a sacred community ritual."},
];

const traditionsData=[
  {emoji:"🌙",name:"Eid Celebrations — Island Style",location:"All islands",desc:"Lakshadweep's Eid celebrations — both Eid-ul-Fitr and Eid-ul-Adha — are the most important festivals of the year for the entirely Muslim island population. The celebrations combine the standard Islamic observances (communal prayers, feasting, visiting family) with distinctively island customs: Kolkali and Parichakali performances in the evening, special island foods (tuna preparations, coconut sweets), and the extraordinary sight of the entire population of a small island gathering on the beach for community celebrations."},
  {emoji:"🎣",name:"Traditional Tuna Fishing — Minicoy",location:"Minicoy Island",desc:"The pole-and-line tuna fishing of Minicoy Island is one of the world's most sustainable fishing traditions — a method that catches one fish at a time with a barbless hook, causing zero bycatch and zero reef damage. The tuna fishing boats of Minicoy venture into the open ocean at night, return at dawn with their catch, and the processing, drying and export of skipjack tuna has been the economic backbone of Minicoy for centuries. The tradition is shared with the Maldives — Minicoy's closest cultural neighbour."},
  {emoji:"🪸",name:"Coral Reef Conservation — Community Protocols",location:"All islands",desc:"The islanders of Lakshadweep have maintained traditional conservation practices for their coral reefs for centuries — reef areas reserved for fishing, seasonal closures, prohibition on destructive fishing methods. After the 1998 coral bleaching event (which killed significant portions of the reef) and the 2004 tsunami, the Lakshadweep Administration established formal Marine Protected Areas and the islanders developed community-based reef monitoring. The result is one of India's most successful examples of community-led marine conservation."},
  {emoji:"🌴",name:"Coconut Harvest Festival",location:"All islands — annual",desc:"The coconut palm is sacred in Lakshadweep — every aspect of island life depends on it — and the annual coconut harvest is marked with community celebration. Lakshadweep produces some of the finest coconuts in India (the volcanic atoll soil and saline water give the coconuts an exceptional flavour). The harvest involves the entire community; coconut climbers (a specialist skill) harvest from tall palms using traditional methods; and the communal processing of copra (dried coconut) is a major community economic event."},
  {emoji:"🌊",name:"Monsoon Season — Island Isolation",location:"All islands — June to September",desc:"The monsoon season — when rough seas cut the islands off from the mainland for weeks at a time — has shaped the character, culture and psychology of Lakshadweep's people profoundly. The tradition of storing food (dried tuna, coconut products, rice), maintaining community solidarity during isolation, and the collective celebration when the seas calm and supply ships arrive has created a distinctive island resilience. The monsoon-stranded communities developed strong oral traditions, music and storytelling that filled the long isolated evenings."},
  {emoji:"⚓",name:"Ship Arrival Celebrations",location:"All islands",desc:"Each arrival of the supply ship from Kochi — the lifeline of every island — is a community event. The ship brings fresh vegetables, rice, medical supplies, electronics and news from the mainland. Children run to the jetty; families wait for letters and packages; the island's entire social life reorganises around the ship schedule. The joy of the ship's arrival, and the community coming together to unload supplies, distribute goods and share news, is one of the most distinctive cultural rhythms of island life — invisible to tourists but central to Lakshadweep identity."},
];

const cuisinesData=[
  {emoji:"🐟",name:"Mas Curry — Lakshadweep Tuna Curry",location:"All islands",desc:"Tuna is the defining ingredient of Lakshadweep cuisine — the skipjack tuna (locally called mas) is eaten fresh, dried, smoked, in curries, as a paste and as a condiment. The mas curry — tuna pieces cooked in a rich coconut milk gravy with local spices, curry leaves and kokum — is the island's most distinctive dish. The flavour is quite different from mainland Indian fish curries — the tuna's firm flesh, the fresh coconut milk, and the specific blend of island spices create a dish of extraordinary depth."},
  {emoji:"🥥",name:"Coconut in Everything",location:"All islands",desc:"Coconut is to Lakshadweep what ghee is to North India or oil to Tamil Nadu — it appears in every dish, every preparation, every drink. Coconut milk forms the base of all curries; grated coconut is added to chutneys, rice dishes and sweets; coconut oil is the only cooking medium; coconut water is the island's natural refreshment; and coconut toddy (the fermented sap of the palm flower) is the traditional drink. The variety of coconut preparations in Lakshadweep cuisine is extraordinary."},
  {emoji:"🍚",name:"Mas Bai — Tuna Rice",location:"All islands",desc:"Mas bai — rice cooked with dried tuna, coconut milk and local spices — is the everyday staple of Lakshadweep, eaten for breakfast, lunch and dinner in different variations. The dried tuna gives the rice a deep, slightly smoky flavour that is entirely distinctive to the islands. Mas bai is the dish that every person who grows up in Lakshadweep remembers as the taste of home — simple, deeply satisfying and impossible to replicate without the specific dried tuna of the islands."},
  {emoji:"🍯",name:"Halwa & Island Sweets",location:"All islands — festivals",desc:"Lakshadweep's sweet tradition reflects both the Kerala mainland influence and the Islamic festive culture — halwa made from rice, wheat or coconut with jaggery and ghee; unnakkai (a steamed rice dumpling filled with coconut and jaggery); ada (steamed rice cakes in banana leaf); and the special festival sweets made only for Eid. The use of coconut jaggery (made from coconut palm sap) rather than sugarcane jaggery gives the island's sweets a distinctive, slightly caramel flavour."},
  {emoji:"🐠",name:"Reef Fish Preparations",location:"All islands",desc:"Beyond tuna, Lakshadweep's reefs provide an extraordinary variety of food fish — red snapper, grouper, parrotfish, rabbitfish, triggerfish and many others. The island cooking traditions for these species reflect centuries of knowledge: certain fish are best cooked dry-spiced; others need coconut milk; some are best grilled over coconut shell charcoal. The coral reef fishing traditions of Lakshadweep are carefully regulated — reef fish are caught only using traditional pole-and-line or handline methods, never nets."},
  {emoji:"🧃",name:"Coconut Toddy & Island Drinks",location:"Traditional community",desc:"Kallu — fresh coconut toddy (the fermented sap of the coconut palm flower) — has been the traditional drink of the islands for centuries, though its consumption sits in complex relationship with Islamic practice. Fresh toddy (mildly alcoholic, consumed within hours of tapping) is nutritionally rich and distinctively flavoured. Neera — the unfermented version — is a sweet, mineral-rich drink consumed for health. Coconut water straight from the green coconut is available everywhere. The islands have no alcohol licence and commercial alcohol is not sold."},
